  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Isaiah 26:16-18",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Isaiah 26:16-18",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". O ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Lord, in trouble ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Amidst the various calamities brought upon them for their correction and especially in their captivity; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "have they",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " — Namely, thy people; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "visited thee ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Come into thy presence with their prayers and supplications; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "they poured out a prayer ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Prayed much and earnestly, as the expression implies; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "when thy chastening was upon them",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " — When thou wast punishing them for their sins. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Like as a woman is in pain, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "&c. — A comparison often used to express men’s consternation under great calamities, from which they cannot deliver themselves; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "so have we been in thy sight ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Such has been our anguish and danger, of which thou, O Lord, hast been a witness. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "We have been with child ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— That is, we have had great expectation of a speedy and happy deliverance, have been big with hopes; and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "we have been in pain ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Have comforted ourselves with this, that the joyful birth would make us forget our misery, but, alas! ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "we have, as it were, brought forth wind ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— We have had the torment of a woman in child-bearing, but not the comfort of a living child. “We have had no good issue of all our pangs and throes; they did not produce deliverance and ease, as in the case of travailing women, but all our own labours proved abortive: in vain we struggled with our enemies, who were still too mighty for us,” and we were utterly unable to effect our deliverance. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "To bring forth wind, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "is much the same kind of phrase with ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "feeding on wind, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "reaping wind, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hosea 12:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Hosea 8:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and signifies, to take a great deal of pains to no purpose. This seems to be spoken of the siege which the Jewish people endured, and of all their other labours and sufferings to prevent their coming under the Chaldean yoke. Thus the attempt of Zedekiah to withstand Nebuchadnezzar we find only brought greater evils upon the country, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 36:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". We ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "have not wrought any deliverance in the earth ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— In our land, where we had far greater advantages than we could have had elsewhere. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Neither have the inhabitants of the world ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— The Assyrians, Chaldeans, or our other enemies; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "fallen ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— By our means.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "26:12-19 Every creature, every business, any way serviceable to our comfort, God makes to be so; he makes that work for us which seemed to make against us. They had been slaves of sin and Satan; but by the Divine grace they were taught to look to be set free from all former masters. The cause opposed to God and his kingdom will sink at last. See our need of afflictions. Before, prayer came drop by drop; now they pour it out, it comes now like water from a fountain. Afflictions bring us to secret prayer. Consider Christ as the Speaker addressing his church. His resurrection from the dead was an earnest of all the deliverance foretold. The power of his grace, like the dew or rain, which causes the herbs that seem dead to revive, would raise his church from the lowest state. But we may refer to the resurrection of the dead, especially of those united to Christ.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Poured out a prayer - Margin, 'Secret speech.' The Hebrew word לחשׁ  lachash means properly a whispering, muttering; and thru a sighing, a calling for help. This is the sense here. In their calamity they sighed, and called on God for help. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "16. visited—sought.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "poured out—(Ps 62:8), as a vessel emptying out all its contents.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "prayer—literally, \"a whispered prayer,\" Margin, \"a secret sighing\" to God for help (compare Jer 13:17; De 8:16).",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
